ign="top"><a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g6qsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 17px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-transform: uppercase; text-decoration: none;">COMMENT</a><br />\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g66sAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 20px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Why Beijing''s antitrust crackdown has little to do with protectionism</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Yang Jian</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408142115502686.bmp" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">SHANGHAI -- Over the last month, the National Development and Reform Commission has launched a slew of antitrust investigations into the pricing practices of foreign automakers. One might logically conclude that China''s central economic planning agency is doing all this to protect domestic automakers. But this notion is misleading even though the NDRC has used questionable tactics to conduct its investigation. (See related story in this newsletter.) <strong>Pictured: Yang Jian is managing editor of <em>Automotive News China</em>.</strong></span><br />\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g6LsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr><td><!-- ad1 -->\r\n<!-- /ad1 -->\r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g7asAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">China to fine Audi $40 million for breaking monopoly law, paper says</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Wire reports</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408142217442907.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">China will fine Audi about 250 million yuan ($40 million) for violating anti-monopoly laws, the <i>21st Century Business Herald</i>, an influential business daily, reported on Thursday. Citing an unidentified source that the paper described as authoritative, the fine to be imposed on the Volkswagen Group subsidiary is calculated based on a percentage of its 2013 car sales in the central province of Hubei.</span><br />\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g7qsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr>\r\n\r\n\r\n<tr><td><!-- ad2 -->\r\n\r\n<!-- /ad2 -->\r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g76sAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">GM faces widening inquiry into pricing practices</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Bloomberg</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408142121567146.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">Shanghai General Motors said China''s antitrust regulator has begun investigating the company amid an industry crackdown that has seen at least seven foreign carmakers cut prices. Shanghai GM, a joint venture between GM and SAIC Motor Corp., has "actively responded" since 2012 to requests from the National Development and Reform Commission''s anti-monopoly bureau and assisted with its investigation, GM told Bloomberg News.</span><br />\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g7LsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g8asAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">European business group slams investigations</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Reuters</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408142216262138.bmp" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">BEIJING -- The European Union Chamber of Commerce in China on Wednesday expressed concern over a recent series of antitrust investigations, saying China appeared to be unfairly targeting foreign firms. Audi AG, BMW AG and Mercedes-Benz are among the automakers scrambling to lower prices for new cars and spare parts in an effort to appease Chinese regulators who have accused some of them of anti-competitive behavior.</span><br />\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g8qsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g86sAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">VW faces probe for sedan defect after mounting owner complaints</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Bloomberg</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408142053524649.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">BEIJING -- China''s quality inspector started an investigation into potential defects of a locally produced Volkswagen AG sedan after mounting complaints from owners. The General Administration of Quality Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine has contacted VW about complaints of broken rear shafts of its Sagitar sedan and asked it to remedy the problem, the regulator said in a statement on its Web site.</span><br />\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g-qsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g-6sAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">VW-brand sales advance 11%, top 200,000 in July</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Automotive News China</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408142106125571.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">Deliveries of VW-brand vehicles in China rose nearly 11 percent year-on-year in July to 210,000 units -- rising at about the same rate as industry sales for the month. For the first seven months, VW-brand sales in China and Hong Kong increased 18 percent to 1.6 million units.</span><br />\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3g-LsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3gAasAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">EV, plug-in hybrid output soars tenfold in July</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Automotive News China</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408142103484063.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">Automakers, aided by government subsidies, produced 5,799 electric vehicles and plug-in hybrids in China last month, ten times the total from a year earlier. Last month automakers built 3,728 EVs, 17 times the number a year earlier, according to the Ministry of Industry and Information Technology, the regulator of China''s auto industry. Output of plug-in hybrid cars totaled 1,036 units. No plug-in hybrid vehicles were produced in July last year.</span><br />\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3gAqsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3gA6sAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">ZF launches big expansion at Shanghai r&d center</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Automotive News China</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408142131086530.bmp" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">SHANGHAI -- German parts supplier ZF Friedrichshafen AG is investing 50 million euros (412 million yuan) to quintuple the size of its Shanghai headquarters and research hub to accommodate offices, laboratories and test benches. The center will have 54,000 square meters of floor space, up from 11,000 square meters now. The expansion will allow the facility to design global products for ZF.</span><br />\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3gALsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr></table>\r\n<br />\r\n<table width="415" align="center" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0"><tr><td style="font-size:13px;font-family: Trebuchet MS,sans-serif;font-style:italic; margin-bottom:5px;"></td></tr></table><br />\r\n\r\n</td></tr></table>\r\n</td><td valign="top" width="300">\r\n<a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ugmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3gBasAq8AMa" target="_blank"><img src="http://oas-central.realmedia.com/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/anoemail/HENKEL_CHMR_11_0814/140523094157@x30" border="0"></a>\r\n\r\n<br /><table><br /><hr width="99%" size="2" />\r\n<div align="center"><span style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-weight: bold; color: #000000; text-align: left; line-height: 16px; text-decoration: none;">&nbsp;TOP 10 HEADLINES<br />OF THE LAST WEEK</span></div><br /><tr><td valign="top"><a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3gBqsAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 16px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Toyota, Honda cut spare part prices as antitrust probe expands</a><br /><hr width="95%" size="2" /></td></tr>\r\n<tr><td valign="top"><a   href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7-2qef2926%7CV3gB6sAq8AMcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 16px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">How companies cope with the latest crackdown</a><br /><hr width="95%" size="2" /></td></tr>\r\n<tr><td valign="top"><a   href=