cj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-rE6sCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 20px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">China finds Mercedes-Benz guilty of price fixing, report says</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Reuters</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408182209007822.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">SHANGHAI -- Mercedes-Benz has been found guilty of manipulating prices for after-sales services in China, the official Xinhua news agency reported, adding to pressure on foreign carmakers in the world''s largest auto market. Daimler, the parent company that makes the luxury Mercedes-Benz cars, said on Monday it was cooperating with authorities and declined to comment further.</span><br />\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-rELsCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr><td><!-- ad1 -->\r\n<!-- /ad1 -->\r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-rFasCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Dealers cheer regulators'' drive to curb automakers'' pricing power</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Reuters</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">BEIJING -- An antitrust probe into global automakers is being cheered on by car dealers in China, who say that companies such as Audi and Mercedes-Benz have exploited their dominance to boost profits in ways that would not be tolerated in Western markets.</span><br />\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-rFqsCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr>\r\n\r\n\r\n<tr><td><!-- ad2 -->\r\n\r\n<!-- /ad2 -->\r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n<tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-rF6sCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Audi faces 250 million yuan fine for breaking anti-monopoly laws</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Reuters</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408182212013579.bmp" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">SHANGHAI -- China will fine German premium auto brand Audi 250 million yuan ($41 million) for violating anti-monopoly laws, the <i>21st Century Business Herald</i>, an influential business daily, reported. Citing an unidentified source that the paper described as authoritative, the newspaper said the fine to be imposed on Audi is based on a percentage of its 2013 car sales in the central province of Hubei.</span><br />\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-seqsCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-se6sCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Volvo, with cigars and crystal, eyes China''s rich with XC90 overhaul</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Reuters</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408182204097423.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">GOTHENBURG, Sweden -- With headlights shaped like Thor''s hammer and space for a humidity-controlled cigar case, Volvo''s new cars are sporting luxury features and designer glitz to catch the eye of the booming Chinese market and shed their safe-but-dull skin. The redesigned XC90 SUV to be launched on Aug. 26 will make or break a company moving into a premium market dominated by German rivals.</span><br />\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-seLsCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-sfasCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Geely, Volvo chairman says auto industry needs more competition</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Bloomberg</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408182206579509.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">Bring it on. That''s the message Li Shufu, the Chinese billionaire chairman of Volvo Cars, wants the government to give competitors in the largest auto market. "It''s best if it''s completely open, like in the U.S. and Europe; whoever wants to produce cars can do it," Li, who''s also chairman of carmaker Geely Automobile Holdings, said in an interview. "This is fair to us, it''s fair to everyone. It would completely allow the role of the market and perhaps we will develop better."</span><br />\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-sfqsCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-sf6sCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Mazda''s July deliveries rise 36% on strong demand for new models</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Automotive News China</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408182151252049.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">Mazda Motor Corp.''s China sales surged 36 percent to 15,934 vehicles in July. The results were driven by two models the company introduced in China in May -- the Mazda6 Atenza and the Mazda3 Axela, officials with the automaker''s Shanghai office said. In the first seven months, Mazda''s China sales rose 22 percent year-on-year to 114,786 units.</span><br />\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-sfLsCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-sgasCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Daimler recalls 50,000 Smart cars to inspect, repair V-belt</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Reuters</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408182215174596.jpg" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">FRANKFURT -- Daimler is recalling 50,000 Smart microcars in China, at the request of the country''s General Administration of Quality Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine. The regulator identified that vibrations can cause the V-belt, an engine component that drives the cooling fan and the alternator, to tear on certain models and has requested that these cars be recalled, a Daimler spokesman said.</span><br />\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-sgqsCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-sg6sCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">China''s Brilliance mulls Italy car plant, prime minister says</a><br />\r\n<span style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 22px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">Reuters</span>\r\n</td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.autonewschina.com/images/S000201408182200269333.bmp" align="left" hspace="4" width="100" />\r\n<span style="font: normal 14px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; text-align=left;">ROME -- Italian Prime Minister Matteo Renzi said Chinese carmaker Brilliance China Automotive Holdings has expressed an interest in opening a plant in Italy. Speaking to reporters during a visit to the town of Termini Imerese in Sicily, the site of a former Fiat Group vehicle production plant, Renzi said that the government had established contacts with Brilliance during a recent visit to China.</span><br />\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-s%7CqsCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 12px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 14px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt; More</a><br /><br /></td></tr><tr><td valign="top">\r\n<a  href="http://crainnewsalerts.com/portal/wts/ucmcj%5E%5Ee7E%7Cqef2E%7CL%7CV-s%7C6sCBkqzcxAXFcD-zXMYm" target="_blank" style="font: bold 17px/normal Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 19px; color: #000000; text-align=left; text-deco